Financial Capital
Perez didn=E2=80=99t just write about Technological Revolutions, but how th=
ey relate to Financial Capital. In the Installation Phase, financial capita=
l takes risks on new technologies and business models in search of higher r=
eturns. In the Deployment Phase, production capital helps scale proven tech=
nologies and business models in exchange for lower, more predictable return=
s.=C2=A0
In fact, Perez argues that technological revolutions, which occur every 50-=
60 years, are driven by the availability of Financial Capital.=C2=A0
I think it=E2=80=99s notable, then, that we=E2=80=99re seeing the rise of v=
enture capital megafunds, each with billions or tens of billions of dollars=
 under management, which need to invest in very large opportunities in orde=
r to generate returns on that capital. Personally, I think the argument tha=
t those funds are simply seeking management fees is lazy and uncreative.=C2=
=A0
What if large pools of capital are needed to fund and support Vertical Inte=
grators?=C2=A0
Often, these companies will need more money upfront than a traditional soft=
ware company, and they will take longer to bring a product to market and ge=
nerate revenue, which means that they need capital partners who can continu=
e to support the company with checks larger than smaller funds can write.=
=C2=A0
Surprisingly, once they gain momentum, Vertical Integrators can grow with s=
urprisingly little dilution. For example, assuming that SpaceX raised its f=
irst outside capital at around a $150 million valuation in 2005 (PitchBook =
has valuation data on all rounds except that one), it=E2=80=99s experienced=
 just 43% dilution over twenty years!
The flip side of that even as investors wrote much larger checks into the c=
ompany =E2=80=93 over $9 billion in total =E2=80=93 they did so at increasi=
ngly high valuations. A small fund that needs to aim for higher multiples w=
ould have been better off writing one check and bowing out from a MOIC (mul=
tiple on invested capital) perspective =E2=80=93 just investing in that fir=
st round would give you a 680x! =E2=80=93 but the company would have run ou=
t of money if all investors thought that way. Megafunds, on the other hand,=
 could deploy enormous amounts of capital to defend their ownership and fue=
l the company, and be very happy putting large sums of money to work at a 2=
0x MOIC.=C2=A0
Anduril is earlier in its journey, but the numbers seem to be following a s=
imilar pattern.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s a little in the weeds, but the point is that the right kind =
of funding exists to support unproven Vertical Integrators that can support=
 massive valuations if they work, a necessary ingredient at the beginning o=
f a new Techno-Economic Paradigm.
I am mostly saving predictions and implications for Part III, but this feel=
s like an appropriate place to make one:=C2=A0
Megafunds will increasingly team up and pick one winner per vertical that t=
hey support in its fight against well-resourced incumbents.=C2=A0=C2=A0
This has precedent. JP Morgan played a massive role in picking and shaping =
the winners of the Second Industrial Revolution, from pulling together US S=
teel into the world=E2=80=99s first billion-dollar corporation to forming G=
eneral Electric and International Harvester to financing Theodore Vail=E2=
=80=99s pursuit to turn AT&T into the universal service for telephone commu=
nications across the United States.=C2=A0
Wildly ambitious plans require deep financial backing.=20
With Vertical Integrators, unlike traditional software companies, there wil=
l be less fighting among startups, and more cohesion among big players in t=
he startup ecosystem against common legacy enemies. Anduril is backed by Fo=
unders Fund, General Catalyst, Lux Capital, a16z, 8VC, Valor Equity Partner=
s, and Thrive Capital, as a recent example. Hadrian is backed by Founders F=
und, Lux Capital, and a16z. This will happen more frequently.=C2=A0
That doesn=E2=80=99t mean the anointed Vertical Integrator will win that fi=
ght, but to have the best shot, they=E2=80=99ll need to concentrate talent =
and capital in one company. More than in other startup categories, there wi=
ll be a fairly clear separation between the best and the rest by the Series=
 A or Series B.=C2=A0
The counter to this might be the big AI labs. OpenAI, Anthropic, and xAI ha=
ve raised billions of dollars each, and the same investors have backed mult=
iple AI labs =E2=80=93 closed and open. I think the reason for that is that=
 the race to AGI, or at least the most powerful models, is just that: a rac=
e. While competitors like Meta and Google are incumbents, they are not incu=
mbents in LLMs. And it=E2=80=99s debatable whether companies like OpenAI ar=
e Vertical Integrators; instead, they may be providing a key factor of prod=
uction that gets commoditized over time. The prize may be so large that mul=
tiple $100B+ winners emerge, and there will always be frenzy at the beginni=
ng of a new TEP.
Regardless of how you classify foundation models, it=E2=80=99s clear that t=
he Financial Capital is prepared to fund the necessary speculation that com=
es in the early stages of a new Techno-Economic Paradigm.=C2=A0
Why Vertical Integrators Now
We covered a lot today, so we=E2=80=99ll pause here to catch our breaths be=
fore coming back for more in Part III.=C2=A0
There are a few main takeaways from today=E2=80=99s Part II:=C2=A0
We may be near the end of the previous Techno-Economic Paradigm and the beg=
inning of a new one.=C2=A0
New TEPs =E2=80=93 and new industries and product needs =E2=80=93 demand ve=
rtical integration.=C2=A0
Vertical Integrators founded at the beginning of new TEPs tend to be the la=
rgest companies founded during that TEP.=C2=A0
They create the conditions for many new businesses as industries modularize=
 to improve costs and efficiency, but these modular businesses typically ar=
e not as large as the Vertical Integrators that enabled them.=C2=A0
Building modularized businesses =E2=80=93 software or otherwise =E2=80=93 t=
o try to improve processes from the dying TEP are likely doomed to fail. Wh=
olly new systems are needed.=C2=A0
Vertical Integrators are necessary at the beginning of a new industry or in=
 the beginning of a new Techno-Economic paradigm for a few reasons:=C2=A0
New TEPs involve a constellation of multiple new, interrelated technologies=
 that aren't yet well understood or standardized.=C2=A0
The full potential of new technology combinations isn't yet known, requirin=
g experimentation and control over multiple components to iterate quickly.
There's a lack of established supply chains and ecosystems for these new in=
puts.
Intrepid entrepreneurs will need to vertically integrate to figure out how =
to build the new products the market needs, and the new business models to =
support them, before the rest of the market can come in to improve processe=
s and modularize inputs in order to bring down costs and improve performanc=
e.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s the hard way, but as Chris Power and others have discovered by=
 trying the =E2=80=9Ceasy=E2=80=9D way first, it may be the only way to rea=
lly make a dent in critical physical industries.
To that end, I=E2=80=99d like to leave you with a hypothesis: if you want t=
o build a Vertical Integrator, now is the time.=C2=A0
The first company in each category to vertically integrate enough with a so=
lution that is much cheaper, better, or faster than the incumbent will be w=
ell-positioned to win that category and build a very large business, and it=
 will be difficult for others to displace them.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s a lot of nuance needed in that statement. The first Vertica=
l Integrator in a category certainly won=E2=80=99t always be the winner. Lo=
ok at Katerra [ https://substack.com/redirect/89897e2b-f2f2-44e8-b34a-d2ba0=
00189b7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] in housing construction as one example. In fact, the first often =E2=80=
=9Ctakes the arrows,=E2=80=9D learning lessons that successors will incorpo=
rate into their models.=C2=A0
Just launching a Vertical Integrator at the right time isn=E2=80=99t enough=
=2E=20
The Vertical Integrator needs to combine the new technologies in just the r=
ight way to create a much better solution with structurally superior unit e=
conomics, at reasonable scale, on paper to start. It needs to build the tea=
m that can turn =E2=80=9Con paper=E2=80=9D into =E2=80=9Cin practice,=E2=80=
=9D and attract the investors willing to fund the company until it gets to =
the scale that it can compete (and raise debt or project financing to scale=
 further). It needs to overcome regulatory roadblocks thrown in its way by =
the incumbents. And it needs a product so much better, cheaper, or faster t=
hat customers and partners, used to doing something the old way, are motiva=
ted to switch to something new.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s worth remembering that we are not the first generation of inte=
lligent people interested in applying new technology to make better product=
s. Read Kochland, Titan, Cable Cowboy or any number of books and biographie=
s on very large companies built at the turn of previous TEPs. Many of those=
 companies are still operating, and will fight back vigorously, often attem=
pting to incorporate the same technologies into their products and processe=
s. It will be a battle.=20
But if the Vertical Integrator can pull all of that off =E2=80=93 and often=
 much more =E2=80=93 all of those challenges become a moat, and advantages =
compound. It becomes very hard to displace a TEP=E2=80=99s first big winner=
s until a new Techno-Economic Paradigm emerges some time fifty years into t=
he future (or potentially sooner, if the cycles speed up).=C2=A0
Why that is is a conversation for Part III.=20
Today, we talked about the theoretical and practical Why Now for Vertical I=
ntegrators.=C2=A0
In Part III, we=E2=80=99ll dive into the specifics: challenges they face, t=
he advantages they might have, what it takes to build them, and what the im=
plications of all of that might be.
