5em 0; position: relative;"><strong>The Theoretical Why Now&#160;</strong><=
/h3><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;">There are times for modularization and times for vert=
ical integration. Neither is good or bad, right or wrong. The predominance =
of one form over another in a given industry lays the groundwork for the em=
ergence of the other.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">IBM&#8217;s vertically int=
egrated, mainframe-centric approach gave way to the modularized personal co=
mputer industry, with Windows running with equal ease on Dell or Compaq har=
dware, as one of many examples.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55)=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Vertical integra=
tion is typically the dominant strategy when industries are in their early =
stages or undergoing significant transformation, when market structures are=
 unclear, supply chains are underdeveloped, and new technologies are emergi=
ng. Companies that can control more of the value chain can introduce new pr=
oducts that the market needs faster and more efficiently.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">As industries mature, modularization typically prevails. It allow=
s for specialization, flexibility, and cost efficiency. Companies typically=
 focus on specific parts of the value chain, and rely on partners for the r=
est.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Then, the system gets increasingly complex =
and fragile over time, and is unable to respond to changing conditions quic=
kly enough, necessitating a new wave of vertical integration.</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">You can see this pattern play out within specific industries, and=
 even within specific companies, over time. Carter commented on both the in=
dustry level &#8211;&#160; &#8220;In Clay's context, if the market is seeki=
ng new features/product, vertical takes off. If price, horizontal takes off=
&#8221; &#8211; and the company level:&#160;</p><blockquote style=3D"border=
-left: 4px solid #0c2427; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; mar=
gin-left: 20px;"><em>1st generation leadership (Musk, Bill Boeing, James Mc=
Donnell, Palmer Luckey) are vertical system integrators. Then the 2nd gener=
ation shows up. Who are process innovators. They reduce cost. They modulari=
ze. They subcontract. All the time looking awesome because they made the 1s=
t generation lower cost and better. Then the 3rd generation shows up. They =
are product innovators, or losers. Creative Destruction takes off. The incu=
mbent resets or gets destroyed.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><spa=
n>He pointed me to the work of James Utterback and William Abernathy, who i=
n 1975 co-authored a paper titled </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.co=
